column168: SHPX 203448 was noted by carrier personnel with product vapor around top of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and found 3 of 3 safety vent assembly flange nuts missing.  The flange bolts were in place with no nuts securing the bolts.  Normal switching operations had caused the vent assembly to become dislodged and lean allowing product vapor to escape.      The vent assembly was repositioned, the flange nuts replaced and properly secured stopping the release.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 07/02/10 at 06:51 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Acca yard in Richmond, VA discovered     GATX 24069, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, RPMG, LLC, VA EOC and NRC was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010070200053). CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager, Mike Austin and HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, were dispatched to the scene and found a defective manway gasket. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. The CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager replaced the gasket and the leak stopped. The car was released for transport.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident.     Cause Code:209  NARRI: 5 (3+3+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: On 07/03/2010 JRSX 1009 was reported as leaking in the Davidson Yard. Reg. Mgr. M. Kelly responded and found that the car was leaking from the connection between the bottom outlet valve and the bottom of the tank. Kelly was unable to stop the leak so he transloaded the product out of the car. After the car was transloaded and cleaned Kelly inspected the car and found that four of the eight Bolts that secured the bottom outlet valve to the tank were less than tool tight and that the gasket between the bottom outlet valve and the tank was severely deteriorated to the point that it would not contain the product. The car is B/O awaiting repairs.

column168: A rolloff container was staged at the ten day storage lot of the intended waste disposal facility.  During a routine yard check, a small amount of material was found to have leaked onto the ground.  A response crew was notified, they donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and shovelled the material back into the container.  The area on the ground was cleaned up and also placed into the container.  The rear seal on the box had leaked due to deterioration and aging.  The container was unloaded at the intended waste disposal facility and then placed out of service for the maintenance department to replace the rear gasket.
column169: The container showed no signs of problems at the time of pickup.  The deterioration of the rear gasket was in an area that would not have been readily apparent to the driver.  The maintenance department has been instructed to do a more thorough job of checking the seals when the boxes are in for repair.

column168: CGTX 26214 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Local emergency responders made an initial entry and were unable to isolate and stop the odor release.  Emergency response contractor, React Environmental responded and found the manway cover bolts less than tool tight allowing a small amount of liquid and vapor to escape.  The manway cover bolts were all tightened two full turns stopping the release.      A cam lock cap on the vapor line was not properly secured however this defect did not contribute to the release of liquid or vapor as the vapor valve was properly closed and secured.      After securing the manway bolts the car was moved to check for leaks with no liquid or vapor release noted.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During off loading a fork lift operator punctured a lead acid battery that was staged on a pallet with the forks of the lift causing acid to leak onto the floor of the trailer. The pallet had a cracked plank, this caused the battery to drop below the top of the pallet and be in a position where the forks of the lift could contact it. The operator did not observe that the battery was in this position and when he attempted to slide the forks into position the battery casing was breached.
column169: 1. The shipper was contacted and informed of the incident and instructed to use pallets of good integrity.  2. The forklift operator was instructed to more throughly note the condition of pallets and cargo prior to off loading, paying special attention to pieces that may have shifted/moved during transit.

column168: Tank car GATX 70271 was discovered with product sprayed on the sides of the tank car and several drops scattered on the ground in the immediate area at 1430 hours on Friday, July 9, 2010 by PTRA Maintenance of Way personnel. After an initial inspection by PTRA Safety and Environmental Director it was determined that the car was leaking from the manway area when the car was moved and product sloshed inside the car.  M&M Protection was called to inspect the gasket and secure the manway. Upon arrival they determined the gasket had been pinched when the car was secured for transport, allowing product to spray out when it moved.  The gasket was replaced and the manway secured. THe car was pressure washed with a soda ash solution to clean all product off of the side of the car. The ballast in the immediate area was also sprayed to neutralize any ground contamination.     MULTIPLE REPORT  Tank car GATX 21358 was discovered with product sprayed on the sides of the tank car and several drops scattered on the ground in the immediate area at 1430 hours on Friday, July 9, 2010 by PTRA Maintenance of Way personnel. After an initial inspection by PTRA Safety and Environmental Director it was determined that the car was leaking from the manway area when the car was moved and product sloshed inside the car.  M&M Protection was called to inspect the car.Upon arrival they determined that one swing bolt was hanging down not secured, the other two were not tool tight, allowing product to spray out when the car was moved.  The gasket was inspected and reused and two of the manway bolts were properly secured. THe car was pressure washed with a soda ash solution to clean all product off of the side of the car. The ballast in the immediate area was also sprayed to neutralize any ground contamination. The stripped manway bolt was replaced on Saturday, July 10, 2010 thus securing the car for movement to customer.
column169: The freight bill party, SHrieve Chemical, was notified of the incident and is taking measures to prevent future instances. This is the second time in 12 months that their Doe Run Smelting Division has had cars shipped improperly.  Additionally, PTRA is issuing new instructions concerning NARs to all customers.    MULTIPLE REPORT  The freight bill party, Shrieve Chemical, was notified and is taking action to prevent future issues. PTRA is sending new instructions to customers concerning our actions to prevent NARs on PTRA property.

column168: Shipment consisted of multiple cartons on a skid approx 7 ft in length. Only 4 of the cartons contained the hazardous product while the other cartons contained light weight paint related materials. The skid was loaded up on our trailer decking system. The way the skid was stacked, it had all of the weight to one end of the overlong skid. When the individual unloading the skid lifted it from the deck system with the forklift, the heavy end flipped the skid. This caused the 4 gallon cans to burst at the lids.
column169: That we ensure that all hazardous materials are only loaded on the floor of the trailer.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained TILX 194765 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) emanating a product odor. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was immediately notified and inspected TILX 194765. The responder reported finding product wetness at the base of the manway nozzle. The source of the spillage was via the manway closure. The responder checked all manway securement bolts, finding two bolt nuts less than tool tight and these were properly tool tightened. The shipper seal at the manway was intact and not disturbed by the responder during securement activities. Spillage around the manway nozzle evaporated and no ground impact was observed. No further product release was noted from TILX 194765 during subsequent movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On July 19, 2010 at approximately 19:30, while loading a trailer and employee dropped a package containing 2 - 2.5 liter glass bottles of nitric acid.  The inner packagings broke releasing the acid.  The acid reacted with the cardboard causing a brownish vapor.  The immediate supervisor put on a respirator and went in to apply a neutralizer to try and control the spill.  The fumes were still very strong, so the trailer was removed from the building and the fire department was contacted.  Upon arrival at approximately 20:00, the fire department was presented with the Hazardous Materials Shipping Papers for the load, to determine the hazard present.  Infotrac was notified at 20:52 and they contacted the shipper (Seacole) recommending that Bay West Environmental Services be contacted for the clean-up.  Bay West arrived at approximately 01:00 and started the clean-up and the fire department left the scene.  Bay West removed and washed or eliminated any contaminated packages that were in the trailer, then proceeded to wash out the trailer.  The scene was cleared at 05:15.
column169: 1. Immediate (within 24 hours) informational meetings with all employees to discuss what happened, how it could be prevented in the future.     2. Discussions with supervisors on procedures, identify job functions in case of an emergency    3. Evaluate and restock the Hazardous Response Kits - addition of response materials and checklists for keeping boxes stocked.     4. Contact with shipper to make sure Hazardous Materials are packaged properly to avoid incidents.    5. Continued and ongoing training with driver's and warehouse personel to handle packages without incident and reporting procedures.

column168: A BNSF local train crew member was splashed by product droplets expelled from the top of GATX 21429 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) during delivery at the consignee's (Rio Tinto Mineral-U.S. Borax) facility. The BNSF employee was immediately decontaminated at the consignee's on-site health clinic and released with no injury reported. GATX 21429 was carefully moved to the consignee's unloading rack for inspection and cleaning of product spillage atop this tank car. The consignee reported that the three bolt fill hole closure had loose securement bolts and the fill hole gasket was out of position. The consignee's unloading operator replaced the fill hole gasket and properly secured all three fill hole securement bolts. GATX 21429 was unloaded without further incident. The product spillage on the top of GATX 21429 was neutralized and washed off before unloading commenced and also afterwards.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF outbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained NATX 303904 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with fresh product on its side shell. No ground impact from this spillage was reported. Immediate inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder determined that the manway gasket was missing which allowed product to be expelled via the manway closure. All six manway securement bolts were in a tool tight condition. A new manway gasket was procured and applied onto the manway nozzle. The manway closure was resecured. Non-evaporated spillage on the tank car shell was diluted with rainy conditions at the time this response was concluded.

column168: NYK Logistics, acting as a transportation broker, dispatched a carrier to pick up a load of goods on behalf of its customer/shipper, Spectrum Brands.  At the time of order placement by Spectrum, no hazmat commodities were declared.  Pickup was at Spectrum's vendor, Apollo Industries.  Apollo loaded 9 pallets onto trailer and closed trailer for delivery.  Carrier delivered 3 pallets to one of Spectrum's facilities and then 6 others to its final destination location at Spectrum's facility in St. Louis.  Included with the products packed onto the pallets were five, 5-gallon barrels of Gamma55 (as indicated on the BOL provided to the driver by Apollo at pickup).  Upon arrival at final destination and opening trailer, driver noticed that one of the barrels had tipped over and was leaking onto theflooring of the trailer.  After closer inspection, it was noted that the barrel did not have a sealed lid like the other containers; instead it was covered with what appeared to be a shrink-wrap material.  Driver, not realizing that the product could be hazmat as it hadnot been declared such by the shipper or the shipper's vendor, set the drum upright.  He touched the product with his hand and some also splashed onto his face and eye as part of moving the container. Shipper's receiving dock manager responded and placed the driver under a HAZ flush and reportedly also assisted with cleanup of the trailer per MSDS instructions.  Shipper also took custody of the containers and placed in a secured location for inspection.  No one else was injured during this event.  NYK Logistics has requested copies of photos taken at the scene as well as specific information about the potential hazmatreportable commodity (quantities, concentration level, why the one package was sealed incorrectly, etc.).Both Spectrum and Apollo have been fully apprised of the incident and each has advised it is also investigating the incident.
column169: Recommendation to NYK Logistics' customer Spectrum and customer's vendor Apollo to utilize appropriate packaging, labeling and declaration of materials for each and every load.  NYK Logistics will continue to require Spectrum to identify each item being shipped on its behalf and to ensure its vendors understand that all products must be appropriately sealed and labeled prior to shipment.  We have learned after the initial reporting that the amount spilled was less than 1 gallon.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: Improper blocking/bracing contributed to a load shift in transit resulting in a hazmat spill that was detected when the container de-ramped in Portland, OR.  Approximately ten (10) gallons of corrosive liquid, basic, organic, n.o.s. (ethanol amine) Class 8, packing group II was found to be leaking from the container (cofc).  Containers were double-stacked; the leaking container was on top, resulting in corrosive material leaking onto the lower container.  Both containers were taken to the hazmat pit by rail personnel.  Upon inspection of the interior of the container several pallets of hazardous materials were found to have load shifted.  Approximately twenty 5-gallon containers totaling approximately one hundred (100) gallons of ethanol amine were discovered to have spilled, the majority still in the container, the remainder having leaked on the exterior surface of the two containers and on the ground immediately below the containers.  Hazmat contractor was contracted by J.B. Hunt to conduct hazmat containment; contractor dispatched subcontractor to the site to conduct the clean-up efforts.  Photos obtained by subcontractor revealed minimal-to-no load blocking and bracing had been conducted by the shipper; this was the second of two similar incidents involving the same shipper in a span of about two weeks.  Subsequent investigation by J.B. Hunt personnel and by the load consigner, Staples, led to a recommendation to the shipper (Carroll Company) to review their loading practices.
column169: This was the second of two similar incidents involving the same shipper occurring within an approximately two week time span. Both incidents were due to improper blocking/bracing. This issue has been addressed with the shipper and with the consigner; additionally the railroad has begun to inspect shipments originating from this carrier. Shipper has been advised by both J.B. Hunt and Staples how to properly block & brace shipments in the future in order to comply with DOT regulation #177.834(a)

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman observed and reported PLMX 135086 (DOT 112J340W tank car) venting in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected PLMX 135086 finding the pressure relief device (PRD) emanating a product odor. Internal pressure reading at the time of initial inspection was 140 psi and the Midland A-1280 PRD installed atop PLMX 135086 had a pressure setting of 280.5 psi. The side specification stencil indicated that this PRD was last qualified in the year 2007. The responder suspected that deteriorated seat/stem O-rings were allowing product vapor to by-pass the closed PRD. PLMX 135086 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. The responder replaced the seat and stem O-rings within the PRD by 1530 hrs. CDT, 7/07/201 ending the vapor release from the PRD. The O-rings removed appeared flattened or compressed.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 7/11/2010 at 23:55 hours, personnel in the CSXT Rice yard in Waycross, GA, discovered UTLX 9590639, a loaded tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous, producing an odor and a white cloud coming from the top of the protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper, Mississippi Phospates, Waycross Fire Department, Ware County HazMat, GA Department of Natural Resources (Report 62645), CHEMTREC (Report 20100712-00006) and the NRC (Report 947386), were notified of the vapor release.  Eagle / SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, responded to provide air monitoring and an emergency respnse entry team to investigate. Eagle / SWS discovered the B-end liquid valve open  turn and a less than tool tight secondary securement plug. The leak was secured and the car was monitored for 24 hours before released for disposition. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Thomas McKiernon (228-762-3210).     An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Noncompliance Report is not required for this incident.    Note: This incident did require a Special Move for handling UTLX 950639.    Cause Code: 119  NARRI: 5 (5+9+2) x (2+0) = 160

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the  trip, the driver conducted a routine load check and identified material leaking from the trailer onto the vans axel. The driver immediately place an absorbent material down to absorb the free liquid and prevent the spread of the release. Once secured, he notified his home dispatcher and the manager of the fueling facility where the vehicle was parked. The Greeneville Fire Department was called as was a local emergency response company. Upon arrival the emergency response team inspected the trailer and utilizing appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and initiated the removal of containers in order to identify the leaking container. It was discovered that 1 55 gallon drum was leaking from the top lid. The crew placed the leaking containers into a suitable over pack and proceeded to absorb and collect all free liquids. This material was placed into the salvage drums along with all materials used to decontaminate the trailer floor.  Once the clean up was complete, the trailer was reloaded and was sent on to the intended waste management facility where the shipment was received and processed for disposal.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transporttion, no evidence of leaking was observed. It is believed that the drum was overfilled and given the heat that week, expansion caused the container to fail during the course of transportation allowing the material to leak from the container. In order to prevent a recurrence, the individuals that offered the shipment for transportation and the driver in posession of the shipment have been re instructed to ensure that each drum is  inspected before it is accepted for transportation.

column168: On 07/11/2010 at 17:32 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Osborn yard in Louisville, KY, discovered TIMX 26001, a loaded tank car of Ethanol, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Black Velvet Distilling Co., was notified through CHEMTREC (Report 2010-07-11-00052). Pettit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the liquid line pipe attached to the pressure plate was loose. The pipe was removed, cleaned, pipe tape applied and the pipe was then reattached to the pressure plate. The leak was secured and the car was released for transportation. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mike Stroh (403-317-2121) who will request an FRA movement approval to move the car to destination.     This incident did require a special switching move.    No 7.1 will be required as the car will be moving to home shop after it is unloaded to be re qualified       Cause Code: 282    NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) + (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column25: Chemtrade Logistics Inc. by General Chemical Corp.
column168: During a BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard, entrained PVCX 13453 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) was reported with fresh product on its side shell. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected PVCX 13453. Inspection revealed the leak source was at the liquid eduction line's closure cap. This closure cap was not in a tool tight condition (approx. 1 1/2 turns loose). Internal pressure within PVCX 13453 was reduced and the closure cap was properly tool tightened. Securement was completed by 1040 hrs. MDT, 7/13/2010. Observed ground spillage was neutralized with baking soda.  PVCX 13453 was then moved to an isolated location in the railyard for a contractor to neutralize and wipe off product spillage on the tank shell. PVCX 13453 was cleaned of all product spillage by 1600 hrs. MDT, 7/13/2010.  No further product release was evident in subsequent rail movements of PVCX 13453 in the railyard.   The side specification stencil on PVCX 13453 indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2002 and next due in 2012.
column169: This was the second similar incident on the BNSF this year involving PVCX 13453.  Therefore, the shipper was requested to shop PVCX 13453 after unloading to correct the securement deficiencies of the liquid eduction line's closure system (pipe nipple and closure cap).

column168: Univar driver, Jim Unruh, was just beginning to off load  ECOLAB Blend AC 55-5 Red into the customer tank.  All required forms were signed off and approval was given to start the unloading process by Tolleson Dairy personnel.  The Dairy operator was on a deck near the top of the tank which was taking the product when he immediately noticed product coming out of the tank connection on top.  The Univar driver stopped the flow of product as soon as he was notified of the leak.  No more than two gallons of product spilled into Tolleson’s Dairy tank containment area.  The Dairy maintenance department was called to investigate the leak and make the necessary repairs before the blend can be re-delivered.  There were no injuries.
column169: It was noted that the product (approximately 2 gallons) had spilled out of the pipe inlet into the top of the tank when the unloading process had started.  The spill was contained in the tank diked area.  The Tolleson Dairy Maintenance crewe discovered that the gasket had cracked and was in need of replacement.  They believed that the high summer temperatures was involved in the deterioration of the gasket.  ECOLAB and Tolleson Dairy have decided to replace this gasket on a monthly basis during the summer months when the air temperature is extreme.

column168: July 1, 2010: At approximately 2:45pm, during a routine inspection, FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector R. Dedow found tank car DOWX 6580, containing the residue of Corrosive Liquid, Basic, Organic, NOS, venting vapor from the manway cover area.     Car was recently interchanged to Conrail-Bayonne Yard, by the East Jersey Railroad (serving shipper, IMTT).  CR Risk Manager A. Richter contacted IMTT to respond.  Mr. Dedow, along with responding IMTT personnel, inspected the car.  Internal pressure reduced and car okayed by Mr. Dedow to be returned to IMTT for inspection and repair.    Later phone conversation with IMTT advised results from inspection by Union Tank Mobil Repair unit determined the manway cover's teflon gasket was worn, not allowing an adequate seal.  Worn teflon gasket replaced with product-compatible rubber gasket and car resecured, okayed for reshipping back to original destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: A release occurred on 7/15/2010 at 10:45 am while in the process of setting up a Basic Chemical Sulfuric Acid transfer to be loaded on trailer CTL 252.  The loader set up the unloading tee on top of the railcar then failed to close the valves on the product tee before pressurizing the vessel.  This resulted in a product release of estimated 50 gallons: 15 gallons on the asphalt and approximately 35 gallons in the storm drain containment. Once the spill was identified, the Loader immediately closed the product valve on top of the railcar and radioed a code yellow.  The Tampa team immediately began to dam and dike the area with soda ash.  After the spill was contained, the Manager notified the appropriate contacts.
column169: Retrain all employees on transferring corrosive product utilizing blower pac/air compressor work instruction SSP 3025-002-KMMS-ALL and document training on form S1686. Loader is to ensure that all valves on tee fittings are in the closed position after connecting to the railcar. Loaders retrained on never pressurizing a railcar prior to verification that all hoses and fittings are connected.

column168: On 7/16/10 at 8:30 am, a loader was in the process of emptying ferric sulfate solution (13%) from railcar EAGX 28024.  When the air came through the product hose, it shook violently, removing the Driver's reducer fitting from the trailer.  30 gallons impacted the soil in the ferric sulfate loading area, no drains were affected.  Lime was used to neutralize the spill and it was put into two drums for Waste Management to pick up.
column169: Terminal Manager conducted a stand down meeting with all the Loaders on Monday, July 19, 2010 and discussed the following topics: The importance of using Velcro straps all connections to include both the terminal’s and Driver’s fittings. Verifiers need to ensure that all cam locks have Velcro straps before allowing a transfer to start. The importance of using terminal provided equipment to ensure it is properly outfitted with Velcro straps.

column168: Our distributor delivered to us a wood pallet with eight 15 gallon containers of muriatic acid to our warehouse. We loaded the pallet of 8 containers onto our truck. One of the containers was rubbing on the head of a nail on the pallet. It wore a hole through the bottom of the container and the muriatic acid started leaking through the floor of the truck while driving to the customer site. The Wisconsin Highway Patrol pulled the truck over into a rest stop. They called the local fire department who put the leaking container into a larger containment device. They rinsed down the truck and let the truck continue on it's deliveries. No report from the fire department has been received.
column169: Better inspection of pallets upon receiving new ones with product on them in the warehouse.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a truck stop in order to conduct a load check.  During the load check, the driver identified that a container on the trailer had leaked and approximately 15 gallons of a suspected flammable solvent had puddle on the trailer floor.   The driver immediately contained the release using a suitable absorbent material from the vehicles spill kit.  Once secured, all required notification were made which included the management of the truck stop at which the driver was parked, local emergency services and his home dispatcher.  The driver’s home dispatcher sent a response crew to the scene and notified a Corporate Transportation Compliance Representatives who in turn reported the incident to the TN Emergency Management Agency.  While the emergency response crew was en route, the local fire department made the decision to evacuate all trucks that were parked at the truck stop while the spill was being addressed.  It is estimated that between 175 and 200 vehicles departed the truck stop while the spill was addressed.  Upon notification that this action was taken, Corporate Transportation Compliance notified the NRC and advised that an evacuation of the truck stop had been ordered by local authorities.  Once the response team arrived, the team members donned appropriate personnel protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The leaking container was identified and placed into a suitable salvage drum.  All absorbent material and debris generated from the decontamination of the trailer floor was collected and placed within the salvage drum.  This container was secured and reloaded onto the trailer.  Upon completion of the response activity, the vehicle was inspected and was released to continue on its way to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage of leaking was observed.  In order to prevent a recirrence, the driver and shipper have been instructed to insure that a thorough inspection be conducted on each container as it is loaded and to take appropriate actions should a container with suspect structural integrity be found.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: On 07/11/2010 at 09:37 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Hamlet yard in Hamlet, NC, discovered GATX 53343, a loaded tank car of Waste Caustic Liquid, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Merichem Company was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2010-07-11-00023).  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway nozzle gasket was misaligned.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative Leo Richard (713-823-1780). HEPACO opened the manway cover, properly installed the gasket, closed the cover, and tightened the securement bolts/nuts with a wrench.  The railcar was decontaminated and released for it's destination.    This incident did require a special switching move.   A QA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident.  Hazardous Waste Manifest Number 9304483-2.    Cause Code: 208  NARRI: 5 (5+5+1) x (2+0) = 110
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On  07/15/2010 at 01:00 hrs, CSXT conductor Steve M. Register was splashed by product from GAMX 5271 (a loaded tank car of Liquid Ammonium Nitrate) while performing a switch at Big Bend Agri  Services, Cairo, GA. Mr Register washed off the affected area, sought medical attention and was prescribed an ointment. The car was isolated and local facility personnel, Tim Sawyer (cell 229-377-7709) was notified as was CHEMTREC (Report #2010-07-15-00233). Chris Machenberg, CSXT hazardous materials manager, inspected the facility unloading area and tank car to discuss the incident with Tim Sawyer - manway was unsecured allowing product to splash out during switch movement.The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the facilities manager.    This incident did require a special shipping move.  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 200    NARRI Code: 5(5+1+0) X (3+5) = 240
column169: CSX HMS manager Chris Machenberg met with facilities manager Tim Sawyer and discussed the root cause of the incident. Tim Sawyer was informed of the 49 CFR regulations that needed to be complied with. Mr. Sawyer will be issuing new SOPs for the unloading of rail cars with his employees. Also Mr. Sawyer will be placing a decontamination shower outside of the facility fence next to the rail spur of the facility for railroad crews to use in case of an emergency.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While at the Flying J Truckstop in St. George, Utah, a leak was discovered coming from the trailer.  Area was isolated and site was secured.  H2O Environmental of Las Vegas, Nevada was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, free liquid was detected on the asphalt surface beneath the trailer.  Upon inspection of the trailer, one (1) 330-gallon tote was discovered leaking, due to a loose valve.  Approximately 15 gallons of formic acid were released to the trailer floor and asphalt surface.  H2O Environmental neutralized the free product on the affected surface(s), and proceeded to transfer the remaining product into seven (7) 55-gallon drums.  The neutralized product was placed into one (1) 55-gallon drum, and transported off site, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  The seven (7) drums of virgin product were reloaded onto the trailer, and sent on to their destination.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a faulty valve on the tote, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Benchmark Distribution Services will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: A van trailer containing a shipment of hazardous waste returned to the intermediate truck transfer facility for unloading onto another trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.  While making his post trip inspection, the driver noticed a small amount of material leaking from the side of one drum.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  The trailer floor was cleaned up with an absorbent material which was also placed into the salvage container.  The shipment was then unloaded off that trailer and reloaded onto the trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: At the time of pick-up, the driver inspected the containers but failed to identify that a container rated for solids was selected for this shipment.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver will be retrained on container selection and preparation requirements and will be issued disciplinary action as a result of his actions.  In addition, the shipper will be notified of this incident and wil be instructed to insure appropriate containers are used for all future shipments.

column168: On 07/20/2010 at 09:08 hrs., personnel in the Big 4 Yard, in Russell, KY, discovered GATX 72805, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the Lexington spur away from CSXT employees. The shipper, Bayer Material Science, LLC., was notified thru CHEMTREC (Report# 2010-07-20-00114) and shipper representative Chad Blake (304-281-4864) responded to the call. Two CSXT emergency response contractors, HEPACO and Quick Response, were dispatched to the scene and found the fill hole had one bolt less than hand tight and three fill hole bolts less than tool tight. The bolts were tightened, the car was decontaminated and the spill was cleaned up. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.    This incident did require a special switching move  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance is not required for this incident.           Cause Code: 224  NARRI Code: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: When unloading freight from trailer material came across a drum that was empty. Further investigation discovered that a bolt from the trailer floor had popped up during transit and put a dime-size hole in the bottom of the drum contributing to the total evacuation of the drum during transit.
column169: I'm not sure if this was a noticeable problem prior to loading the drum in the trailer or one that developed during the course of transportation, needless to say, trailer floors and integrity should be always inspected prior to loading freight into a trailerto prevent these types of events.

column25: Gessismar Logistics Center - C/O BASF Corp
column168: Our customer service department received received a phone call advising that a tank that the customer previously submitted non hazardous documentation for the day earlier was now moving as a hazardous tank.  The customer provided a dangerous goods declaration for the tank.  The tank had been received by the marine terminal, loaded to the cargo vessel and had sailed when the change was advised.
column169: The customer should have confirmed his details for this shipment prior to dispatching to the trucker and the marine terminal.

column168: During a TAG (The Adherence Group) inspection to verify cargo against the billing, a cylinder of UN1046 helium packaged in a cardboard box with a non flammable label was discovered.  The container was placarded hazardous and had other hazardous cargo but this carton was not on the billing. The shipper was notified and provided an ammended dangerous goods declaration.  The placards were updated to reflect the changes.
column169: Shipper should always audit their documentation against the actual cargo that is loaded in a container.

On 07/17/2010 at approximately 09:06 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Niagara yard, Niagara Falls, NY, discovered OLNX 32025, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, with vapors coming from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Olin Corporation, was called directly to respond. The Olin HazMat Team found the Osseco 165 pound composite rupture disc had been activated and the center section of the disc was blown out. This style PRD has surge protection and was intact. They replaced the Osseco ruptured disc and the residue on top of the tank car was neutralized. Tank car OLNX 32025 was on an interplant move from Olin Corporation plant Buffalo Ave, Niagara Falls, to Foote Yard, via Niagara yard, which is a normal operation for this interplant move.    A QA 7.1 Nonconformance Report is not required for this incident.  This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI Code: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column169: TOTES AND OTHER VARIOUS KINDS OF PACKAGINGS, CONTAINING CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE THEY LEAVE ORIGIN!  ALL TOTES MUST BE BLOCKED, BRACED, SECURED AND SHROUDED FOR ADEQUATE PROTECTION TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE.  USE LOAD LOCK BARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING.  PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF!  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE SURE LIDS ON DRUMS ARE SECURED.

column168: aT APPROXIMATELY 0447 HOURS CDT ON 6TH JULY 2010 I WAS ADVISED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IDENTIFIED AS UTLX 30114 ON TRACK 8 NORTH AT THE BLUE ISLAND YARD IN RIVERDALE ILLINOIS AND RIVERDALE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS RESPONDING AND INDIANA HARBOR BELT (hb) EMPLOYEES WERE ON STAND DOWN AND CLEARED FROM THE AREA OF THE YARD.  UPON ARRIVAL I WAS ADVISED THAT RIVERDALE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD CALLED A HAZMAT BOX ALARM FOR THE DISTRICT.  UPON ARRIVAL TO SCENE DISTRICT HAZMAT TEAM AND MYSELF PROCEEDED TO TRACK #8 NORTH AND NOTED TANK CAR DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA ABOVE THE PLUG.  DISTRICT HAZMAT TEAM DETERMINED THAT NO PUBLIC THREAT EXISTED AND TURN SCENE OVER TO THE RAILROAD FOR HANDLING.  I SUBSEQUENTLY CONTACT IHB HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR "MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL" AND REQUESTED THAT THEY RESPOND. WHILE AWAITING MIDWEST I MITIGATED THE OUTAGE BY ATTEMPTING TO SECURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS AND SUBSEQUENTLY APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS AND BUCKETS TO CAPTURE PRODUCT.  UPON MIDWEST'S ARRIVAL WE AGAIN ATTEMPTED TO SECURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND PLUGS WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS AND AFTER CONTACTING THE SHIPPER WE ORDERED FIVE (5) TANK TRUCKS WITH  PUMPS AND HOSES TO TRANSFER THE LOAD AND WHICH WAS COMPLETED AT 2005 HOURS CDT.  PRODUCT THAT WAS CAPTURED WAS PLACED IN TRANSPORT TRUCKS WITH LOAD FROM TANK CAR.  RESULTING RESIDUAL SPILLAGE ON TRACK AND BALLAST WAS TREATED WITH "SURFACTION" AND ENZYMES.  UNION PACIFIC (UP) TRAIN # MASIH 5 ARRIVED AT IHB RIVERDALE YARD AT APPROXIMATELY 0310 CDT HOURS FOR INTERCHANGE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0435 HOURS IHB MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT BEGAN INSPECTING INBOUND TRAIN IN ACCORDANCE WITH RULES AND REGULATIONS AND NOTED LEAK ON TANK CAR AND MADE NECESSARY NOTIFICATION TO IHB OPERATIONS CENTER AND TERMINAL MANAGER WHO MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS AND STAND DOWN OF THE YARD AREA WHERE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH IHB PROTOCOLS.  DURING THE INCIDENT I ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER FORM THE EMERGENCY CONTACT # ON MOVEMENT RECORD OF CAR AT 409-985-4200 WITH NEGATIVE RESPONSE TO PICK UP AND RECEIVED A RECORDED MESSAGE.  I SUBSEQUENTLY CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND WAS ABLE TO MAKE CONTACT VIA THEIR CHANNELS.  DURING THE INCIDENT FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION (FRA) HAZMAT INSPECTOR, REGION 4, CHICAGO, MICHAEL BENNETT ARRIVED ON SCENE AND CONDUCTED AN FRA INSPECTION OF THIS CAR AND CARS ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPPER THAT WERE PART OF THE CONSIST OF THE TRAIN.  AFTER CAR WAS EMPTIED, I SECURED THE MANWAY, BOSTON OUTLET VALVE AND PROTECTIVE HOUSING THE VALVES WITH CABLE SEALS.  SUPPLIER "TOTAL PETROCHEMICALS USA" OF HOUSTON, TX INDICATED THAT "KMTEX" OF PORT AUTHUR, TX WAS THE SHIPPER OF THE PRODUCT AND TOTAL PETROCHEMICAL WOULD APPLY FOR THE NECESSARY MOVERMENT EXEMPTION OF THE CAR FOR DISPOSITION.
column169: AS PART OF MY INVESTIGATION I CONTACTED TANK CAR MANUFACTURER "UNION TANK CAR" ADVISING THEM OF THE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED SPECIFICATIONS OF THE CAR FOR THIS REPORT UNION TANK CAR WAS ADVISED, THAT TOTAL PETROCHEMICALS USA INDICATED THAT THIS CAR WOULD BE MOVED TO A UNION TANK CAR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR AT WHICH TIME THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND PLUGS WOULD BE INSPECTED TO DETERMINE FAILURE.

column168: On 07/24/2010 at 14:06 hrs., Federal Railroad Administration Inspector Dave Snyder discovered UNPX 128025, a residue covered hopper car of Sodium Chlorate, with the discharge line outlet securement cap hanging by the chain.  No product was observed on the ground near the railcar.  However, residue material was noted in the discharge piping and securement cap.  The car was isolated and shipper, International Paper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report Number 2010-07-24-00053).  FRA Inspector Dave Snyder contacted the shipper in regards to the exception.  Local Mechanical Department forces reinstalled the securement cap and then released the railcar to destination.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance Report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 569  NARRI Code: 5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column168: On 07/24/2010 at 11:27 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Yeoman Yard, in Tampa, FL, discovered car #RTMX 2626, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Oil, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the Consignee, FCC Environmental was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2010-0724-00043).  The Consignee dispatched a response crew to the scene and found that the release was caused by 4 of 8 manway securement bolts/nuts being less than tool tight.  In addition, the railcar was found to have a deteriorated manway gasket.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Kinder Morgan's representative Ezell Watson at 404-350-5018.  FCC Environmentals response team replaced the manway gasket, properly tightened the manway securement bolts/nuts with a wrench, and wiped down the railcar.  The leak was secured and the car was released to destination.      This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident.     Cause Code: 200  NARRI Code: 5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Overfilled
column168: On 07/25/2010 at 16:24 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Florence yard, in Florence, SC,  discovered car #DODX 14474, a loaded tank car of Fuel, Aviation, Turbine Engine, leaking from top of car. The car was isolated and the US Government was notified, via their Department of Defense Hazardous Materials Hotline number (800-851-8061).  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found four of eight manway securement bolts/nuts less than tool tight.  In addition, the railcar was overfilled with no room for product expansion.  The issues were identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Hawthorne Services (US Government Contractor) representative John Gilmer (843-744-3884). Contractor personnel transferred 2,000 gallons from the tank car into a vacuum truck, properly tightened the manway securement bolts/nuts with a wrench, and decontaminated the car. column168: Our unit was traveling east on I-10 near mile marker 136 when traffic started slowing down to observe a disabled vehicle on the shoulder of the Interstate. When the vehicle in front of our unit came to almost a complete stop, our driver realized he could not stop in time to avoid hitting it in the rear. He could not change lanes as there were vehicles on his left side. So the driver swerved over to the shoulder of the interstate and the trailer swung around to the right taking it into the grass and causing it to roll over. The rear washout cap leaked a steady drip of product and the vapor recovery line fitting was bent at the valve where it turns down at a 90 degree going along side of the trailer causing it to leak a steady drip as well. The leaks were stopped after the tanker was transloaded into another trailer. Both leaks lasted for about 8 hours. The product on the ground was neutralized and cleaned up by the response team that was called out to help with the transfer.
column169: On all non insulated trailers the washout cap piping should be long enough so that a Betz Valve could be used in the event that a trailer needs to be transloaded through a washout.

column168: The commercial motor vehicle was backing into a declining loading dock of the facility. When the trailer struck the dock a drum bolt from an adjacent drum apparently punctured a drum causing a small leak near the top chime. When an inspection of the containers occured a leak was noticed. The floor loaded drums restricting the access to the leaking drum were removed to respond to the damaged container. The container was then placed on it's side to stop the leak. The clean up process began, and the leaking container was placed into an 85 gallon overpack drum. The overpack drum was then sealed and labeled with the appropriate markings for future shipment.
column169: A review of the incident was conducted by facility personnel. It was determined that the open head drum bolts were not positioned properly in the trailer so that the position of the bolts were in the void space. This was the contributing factor for the leaking drum. Additional training will be given to drivers to inform customers how to load drums onto trailers. Drivers will also inspect the loading process performed by the forklift drivers as they exit the van trailer. This will enable the drivers to correct any findings that would result in a spill.

column168: While unloading the trailer at the terminal, the client identified that the tote had an apparent malfunctioning valve which in turn released the product. The spill was contained to the inside of the trailer. ERTS was notified of the release, and contacted a contractor for the spill cleanup. The material was containerized and sent for disposal.

Upon delivery of the referenced materials it was discovered that there was a leak from eight of the drums.  Exel contacted Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) to oversee environmental cleanup operations.  ERTS dispatched Evergreen Environmental to the site to overpack the faulty drums.  Due to the solidification of product when the material made contact with air, it was estimated that less than one gallon was released in total from eight drums.

column42: BUTADIENES, STABILIZED OR BUTADIENES AND HYDROCARBON MIXTURE, STABILIZED CONTAINING MORE THAN 40% BUTADIENES
column168: On 07/30/2010 at approximately 23:00 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Aliquippa yard, in Aliquippa, PA, discovered tank car SCMX 4171, a loaded tank car of Butadienes, Stabilized, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Shell Chemical Company was notified via CHEMTREC (Report#2010-07-30-00265). The shipper's representative was contacted, Louis Brzuzy (281-974-7613) at 00:50, 07/31/10. The shipper was advised that CSXT had dispatched emergency response contractor, Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), Washington, PA to respond. SPSI personnel advised security seal "458528" was intact on the tank car protective housing for the top loading/unloading fittings. They reported the pressure in the tank car was 28 psi and outage was 24.5 inches. The interface between the port for the "A" end liquid line valve and its plug was noted to be frosted. SPSI attempted to close the liquid line valve but to no avail. Some of the frosting between the liquid line valve port and its plug was removed allowing the plug to be tightened one (1) to two (2) full turns. Shipper representative Al Deamer (985-507-3384, Al.Deamer@Shell.com) advised CSXT that he would seek FRA Movement Approval to forward this tank car to consignee.     This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA Nonconformance Form 7.1 is required for this incident.     Cause Code: 119  NARRI Code: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A roll-off trailer operated by Clean Harbors Envirronmental servivces, Inc. was transporting a a non DOT specification vacuum box contianing a liquid/solid mixture of hazardous waste to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor’s in transit storage facility bending final deilvery.  WHiel removing the container from the roll-off fraame, a rear seal failed allowing approximatley 2 quarts of liquid to escape from the container onto the vehicle staging area.  Facility personnel immedialtley deployed a suitable absorbent material and absorbed all freee liquirds.  This material was palced back int othe vaccum box.  Facility perosneel then proceeded to ressecure the rear seal on the container and discovered that the gasket ued on the rear seal was old and needed to be replaced.  Facility peronnel repaired the rear seal and secured the closure device for contiued transportation.  Once complete, the container was delivered to the intended waste management facility without incident and the material was disposed of in accordance with all Federal requirements.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transport, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed.  IN order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper has been advised of the incident and it has been recommended that prior to sealing the closure devices on a non DOT specification bulk bin that the each component of the closure device is inspected to insure it is in good working order and is free of any defects that could preclude it from operating as designed.  In addition, the shipper has been advised to secure the device in such a way that all seals are intact and operational.

column168: DRIVER HAD A BLOWOUT ON WESTBOUND I-10 BY EXIT 200.  HE WENT TO PETRO TO GET HIS TIRE FIXED.  THEY NOTICED AN ODOR FROM THE TRAILER SO THEY LOOKED AROUND AND NOTICED A SMALL BUILD UP ON THE REAR BUMPER.  THE GUY ASK OUR EMPLOYEE WHAT WAS IN IT & THEY DECIDED TO MOVE THE TRUCK INTO A SECLUDED AREA.  PETROL CALLED THE ELOY FIRE DEPT. WHICH CALLED 2 HAZMAT TEAMS TO THE SITE.  THEY SAY IT LOOKED LIKE IT WAS A GASKET FAILURE.  THEY REPLACED THE GASKET AND BALFOUR ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  SCOTT AT BALFOUR ENVIRONMENTAL SAID IT WAS LESS THAN A GALLON.

column168: CN transportation department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car UTLX 200889(L / XYLENES) during switching operations at the CN Glenn Yard, Chicago, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the vacuum relief valve stem / spring and other internal components missing, allowing product to escape during movement. Shipper's response contractor responded, new vrv installed, tank car released for movement by the shipper.

column168: Road Manager noted liquid dripping from bottom gates on rail car CSXT 255414 and reported same to Minneapolis Operations Center. Owner of product Transammonia advised and visited site.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING AND TRANSPORTING TANK, A PIECE OF METAL STICKING OUT OF A CART, PUNCTURED THE TANK, CAUSING A SMALL HOLE. LINED SALVAGE DRUMS OF CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED TANK ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.

column169: TOTES, DRUMS, CYLINDERS AND PAILS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACING USING MTY PALLETS, AIR BAGS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  TEMPORARY STORAGE AREAS FOR PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE KEPT IN A SAFE ENVIRONMENT TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE. column168: AROUND 19:30 BRIDGET PEREZ, HAZMAT AUDITOR, PICKED UP A BOX FROM HAZMAT SQUARE AND BROUGHT IT INTO HER OFFICE.  SHE   IMMEDIATELY SMELT A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE BOX AND OPENED IT, NOTICING A LIQUID INSIDE THE PLASTIC BAG THE CANISTER WAS PACKED IN.  SHE THEN NOTIFIED HER SUPERVISOR WHO CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER.  THE RESPONDER DONNED PPE AND RETRIEVED THE BOX.  UPON FURTHER EXAMINATION THE GASOLINE WAS INSIDE THE PLASTIC BAG THE CONTAINER WAS PACKED IN BUT THE METAL CONTAINER DID NOT HAVE ANY HOLES OR CRACKS.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS FOUND AROUND THE CAP BUT THE PLASTIC PLUG INSIDE THE BOTTLE WAS IN WORKING ORDER.  EITHER THE LIQUID LEAKED THROUGH THE BOTTLE SEAMS OR SOME GASOLINE WAS SPILLED ON THE CONTAINER AND PACKED INTO THE PLASTIC BAG BY ACCIDENT.
column169: RECOMMEND TO TEST METAL CONTAINERS PRIOR TO USE OR DO NOT REUSE CONTAINERS.

column168: AROUND 21:25 AN AUDITED HAZMAT BOX CAME DOWN THE HOUSTON TRAILER CHUTE.  THE LOADER PICKED THE BOX UP AND NOTICIED IT WAS WET.  THEN THE LOADER TOOK THE BOX AND SET IT ON THE PLATFORM OUTSIDE HIS TRAILER AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR (BOBBY BUGSBY) WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED A DESIGNATED RESPONDER.  THE RESPONDER PERFORMED PPE AND WENT TO THE SPILL SITE.  AT THE SITE THE RESPONDER NOTICIED THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL LIQUID SPILLED OUTSIDE THE BOX AND ASKED WAS EVERYONE FEELING OK.  THE RESPONDER THEN TOOK LOOSE CAPS AND THE SEAL ON ONE BOTTLE HAD BEEN COMPROMISED.  THE DEFECTIVE SEAL WAS CLEAR PLASTIC ALL THE METAL FOIL HAD BEEN REMOVED PROBABLY FROM CONTACT W/THE LIQUID INSIDE THE BOTTLE.
column169: RECOMMEND THAT ALL BOOTLE CAPS BE CHECKED BY HAND PRIOR TO SHIPPING.  PLASTIC TAPE OR BANDS BE PLACED AROUND AND ON TOP OF BOTTLE CAPS PRIOR TO SHIPPING, AND PLACE AT LEAST 2" OF PACKING (PAPER, AIR BAGS, ETC.) AROUND THE BOTTLES TO PROTECT BOTTLES FROM IMPACT TO THE SIDES OF THE BOX.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading, leak was discovered on the trailer floor.  Apparently, improper loading caused the freight to tip in transit, which resulted in the release of approximately one (1) gallon of free product to the trailer floor.  Area was isolated, and Op-Tech Environmental Services of Syracuse, New York was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival, Op-Tech Environmental applied absorbent material to the free liquid on the trailer floor, which was recovered and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, pending disposal.  Freight was uprighted, bungs tightened, and shipment secured.  Disposal of one (1) 55-gallon drum of cleanup debris will be coordinated directly by Op-Tech Environmental in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported. The following is a supplemental report to Report-E-2010080160, Tracking Number: 501898 Please note, Webb Chemical Service Corporation shall be named as reporting party only, generator/carrier on record shall be named as Sunset Logistics, LLC, 7744 South Division Avenue, Grand Rapids, Ml 49548. According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While unloading, leak was discovered on the trailer floor. Apparently, Sunset Logistics, LLC personnel improperly instructed/loaded the freight inside the trailer, which caused the freight to tip in transit, thus resulting in the release of approximately one (1) gallon of free product to the trailer floor. Area was isolated, and Op-Tech Environmental Services of Syracuse, New York was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival, Op-Tech Environmental applied absorbent material to the free liquid on the trailer floor, which was recovered and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, pending disposal. Freight was uprighted, bungs tightened, and shipment secured. Disposal of one (1) 55-gallon drum of cleanup debris will be coordinated directly by Op-Tech Environmental in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries orexposures reported.
column169: Incident appears to be related to improper loading.  Webb Chemical Corporation will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column17: LINDENS PROPANE INC LINDENS ANHYDRUOS AMMONIA
column168: On 7/5/2010 truck and driver Phil Linden left La Grange at around 11:00 to 11:05 AM. Truck was carrying 2700 gallons of Anhydrous Ammonia to deliver to Simmons farm wagons at 7444 Beach Rd, Medina Ohio. Truck left roadway at around 12:00 PM. Truck overturned and struck trees resulting in drivers death and engine fire. Fire then caused the seats to leak on valves due to melting. Vapor leakage occurred in small quantity not even enough to cause excess flow valve to shut. When we received notification at 2:20 we responded. Eric Linden arrived at 3:15. Follow by John Linden withTransport and Holly Linden with extra Hoses and valves. Eric and John Linden repaired valves onsite and stopped leak. Truck was not evacuated.Truck was then uprighted by World truck and then towed to impound lot at 2:30 AM.

column168: A BNSF train operating on main track 3, derailed 17 railcars. The cause of the derailment was attributed to irregular cross level of track. Included in the derailed railcars was PPRX 55151 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) that derailed on its side; and sustained a large dent and puncture breach near the upper B-end tank head seam. The escaping commodity liquid with vapor from PPRX 55151 ignited and the ensuing fire engulfed PPRX 55151 and a portion of two other adjacent railcars ladened with non-hazardous material. Also, PPRX 55151 came to rest near two unattended BNSF locomotives being used as 'work train power' that were parked in an adjacent siding track. The fire also engulfed both of these locomotives which were later deemed destroyed. Fires were extinguished using fire fighting foam and water by late afternoon on 7/03/2010. The remaining commodity (mixed with foam and water) in PPRX 55151 was removed and placed in Frac Tanks for appropriate disposal. Impacted ballast and ground soil were excavated and temporarily stored near the derailment site for disposal profiling.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUEFIED OR AMMONIA SOLUTIONS RELATIVE DENSITY LESS THAN .880 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 50 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: On 07/27/2010 at 05:10 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard, in Waycross, GA, discovered PLMX 135231, a loaded tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous, emitting an odor from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Transammonia, Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC (Report# 2010-07-27-00035). Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the odor was being released from the Pressure Relief Device Valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Angie King (813-261-0600). Eagle/SWS personnel dissembled the PRD Valve, removed and cleaned the O-Rings, reassembled the valve, then tested for leaks. Since Eagle/SWS is not a qualified repair facility, the shipper applied for a FRA Movement Approval to forward the railcar onto destination where it will be off-loaded and then inspected by Rescar. This incident did not require a special switching move. A QA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident. Cause Code: 414 NARRI Code: 5 (5+9+2) x (2+0) = 160
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported product splashed from the fill hole atop UTLX 125078 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped awaiting inspection from a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder reported no shipper seals applied to the fill hole cover; all three fill hole securement bolt nuts were less than tool tight; and the fill hole gasket was not properly positioned (overhanging) and cut along the gasket edge. The responder installed a new fill hole gasket and properly tool tightened all fill hole securement bolt nuts. Spillage atop UTLX 125078 was neutralized with a baking soda/water solution and wiped. No ground impact was evident. BNSF seal numbered 002430 was applied to the fill hole cover. The safety vent was also inspected and the frangible disc was intact. BNSF seal numbered 002425 was applied to the safety vent. Response was concluded by 1600 hrs. CDT, 7/19/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported product odor emanating from EPCX 3332 (DOT 105J300W tank car) in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was immediately called to inspect EPCX 3332. The responder could not detect product odor from ground level, but only at the valve housing area atop EPCX 3332. The responder reported that the valve housing's cover shipper seal (HUTCH 106945) was intact. Valve inspection revealed that both liquid valve handles were 1/2 turn from being fully closed with one liquid valve's closure plug not tool tight. There was product icing (auto-refrigeration) around this valve with the loose plug. The responder closed the liquid valves and tool tightened the loose closure plug. The responder also found the vapor valve handle 1/2 turn from full closure with its closure plug tool tight and the vapor valve was closed. After securement was completed, no further product odor was detectable.   BNSF seal numbered 7013022 was applied to the valve housing. Response was concluded by 2239 hrs. CDT, 7/19/2010. EPCX 3332 was held in isolation overnight for observation and since no further product odor was detectable,  EPCX 3332 was released to proceed to its destination 7/20/2010 late morning.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew member in the railyard reported inhaling product vapor fumes emanating from PROX 14974 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car). The BNSF employee immediately left the area where PROX 14974 was standing. No medical treatment was pursued by this employee and no injury resulted from this inhalation exposure. PROX 14974 was cordoned-off in the railyard until BNSF contract responders inspected PROX 14974. The responders reported no product odor from ground level near PROX 14974. Inspection of the top fitting area revealed fill hole cover with seal identified as Bayer 103824 intact. All three fill hole securement bolt nuts were found only hand tight. The fill hole gasket was found out of alignment (off-center). The fill hole gasket was removed, cleaned and properly repositioned. The fill hole cover was closed and all securement bolt nuts were tool tightened. Seal SRS 000357 was applied onto the fill hole. All other top fittings were inspected and found secure. A small amount of liquid product observed atop PROX 14974 was neutralized with a soda ash/water solution and wiped. Response was concluded by 0810 hrs. CDT, 7/20/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: OUR DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID UNDER TRAILER WHILE STOPPED AT PILOT TRUCK STOP.  DRIVER CONTACTED DISPATCH AND CLEAN HARBORS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT.  DRIVER THEN USED FLOOR DRY TO CONTAIN LEAK.  CLEAN HARBORS DISPATCHED 1ST REPONSE TO THE SCENE.  1ST RESPONSE ASSESSED THE PROBLEM.  LEAKING DRUM WAS LOACATED, PUNCTURE WAS TEMPOPRARILY STOPPED WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD AND THEN OVERPACKED IN A 95-GALLON DRUM.  SEVERAL OTHER DRUMS OF MINERAL OIL AND WATER, CLOSE TO THIS DRUM, WERE SUSPECTED OF LEAKING BUT NO PUNCTURES LOCATED SO THEY WERE ALSO  OVERPACKED.  ANOTHER DRUM WAS ASSESSED AS HAVING A LOOSE RING, RING WAS TIGHTENED TO PREVENT FURTHER LOOSENING.  1ST REPONSE UNLOADED CONTENTS OF TRAILER ONTO PLASTIC SHEET, CLEANED FLOOR WITH PADS AND X-SORB AND PUT CLEANING MATERIALS IN A 55-GAL POLY.  ANOTHER DRUM OF MINERAL OIL HAD A BAD SEAL AT THE BUNG AND A PLUG WAS ADDED TO HELP INSURE SEAL.  TOTAL LEAKAGE ONTO GROUND AND IN TRAILER WAS APX 2 GALLONS.  TOTAL TIME INVOLVED WAS APX 6.5 HOURS.
column169: DRIVER FOLLOWED PROPER PROTOCOL AFTER SPILL BUT HE SHOULD HAVE BEEN MORE DILIGENT WHEN RECEIVING THE LOAD AND HE HAS BEEN VERBALLY WARNED AS TO THE DANGERS OF NOT FOLLOWING COMPANY PROTOCOLS FOR INSPECTING LOADS BEFORE ACCEPTING WHILE AT THE SHIPPER.  HE WAS ALSO MADE AWARE THAT FURTHER VIOLATIONS WOULD BE ADDRESSED MORE SERIOUSLY.  CLEAN HARBORS WAS ALSO MADE AWARE OF THEIR NEED TO BETTER INSPECT AND INSURE PACKAGE INTEGRITY PRIOR TO LOADING.

column168: Trailer number 319-5109 was discovered leaking in the yard by the line driver Bryce Fewkes.  Bryce was hooking said trailer for a line run.  A very small spot of clear coat was directly under the trailer on the ground.  I had Mr. Fewkes put the trailer to the dock for further investigation.  We discovered a pallet half way up in the trailer with a bottom 5-gallon can crushed due to the weight of the other cans that were stacked on top.  A very small pin-hole leak was discovered and the can was removed from the pallet.  Most likely the can was crushed when the trailer went over a bump in the road.  Several other cans on the bottom of the same pallet showed signs of being stressed due to the weight of the other cans sitting on top.  We rebuilt the pallet, putting the cans the were on the bottom on top so as not to jeopardise any other cans on the remainder of the trip.  There was no way to tell how long it had been leaking but since there was only a small amount of discharge it probably happened on the leg from Salt Lake City to Boise.
column169: My suggestion would to limit the amount of cans stacked on top of each other.  Or at least how many METAL cans.

column168: Trailer 317-5825 was opened and right away we saw a white substance on the floor underneath pro# 157170974. I was instructed to not touch the freight until I got instructions as to how to clean upthe substance. Once I received instructions, we proceeded in cleaning up the substance by sweeping it into a salvage drum and placing the leaking bags in the same drum. While we were cleaning up the powder, we noticed the powder seemed to be leaking from the seams of the bags. It became clear this spill was not caused by anyone working at Con-way. column168: THE TANKER WAS TRAVELING AT A SPEED OF 45 MPH WHILE IN A CONSTRUCTION ZONE ON INTERSTATE 64 AROUND MILE MARKER 94.  IT WAS RAINING EXTREMELY HARD AND THE DRIVER (BOBBY CALLIHAN) STATED THAT HE WAS BEHING FOUR AUTOMOBILES WHICH WERE FOLLOWING AN EIGHTEEN WHEEL VAN BOX.  THE VAN BOX STARTED TO HYDROPLANE SIDEWAYS AS THE FOUR AUTOMOBILES STARTED HITTING THEIR BRAKES.  BOBBY BEGAN BREAKING AND STARTED HYDROPLANING AS WELL, HE THEN RECOVERED AND THE CARS STARTED BREAKING ONCE AGAIN AND THIS TIME ALL HE COULD DO WAS TRY TO VEER TO THE SHOULDER AND NOT RUN OVER THE AUTOMOBILES.  ONCE ON THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY THE WET EARTH GAVE AWAY AND ROLLED THE TRUCK AND TANKER INTO THE DITCH WHERE IT BEGAN TO SKID TO A STOP.  THE TANKER WAS LOADED WITH FIVE THOUSAND GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND THREE THOUSAND GALLONS OF DIESEL.  THE TANK AND PIPING HELD WELL BUT THE VENT FAILED AND BEGAN TO DRIP PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DRIP OF PRODUCT LASTED APPROXIMATELY FORTY FIVE MINUTES BEFORE THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW COULD GET ON SITE AND CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. THE CREW QUICKLY INSTALLED ABSORBENT PADS AND TOOK OTHER MEASURES TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND.  HOLES WERE CUT INTO THE SIDE OF THE TANKER AND ALL THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANKER.  THE TRUCK AND TANKER WERE THEN LIFTED UP RIGHT AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: During the transfer of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank, our transfer hose developed a hole releasing about 5 gallons. The driver immediately stopped the transfer.  Absorbent was put on the spill and shoveled up.  Driver was able to position the cargo tank closer to the storage tank and removed the bad section of hose to complete the delivery.

The driver connected the product hose to the customer’s product line by securing the flange using an “X” pattern to tighten the bolts on the flange.  The air line hose was connected to the chicago fitting on the air inlet line and the external valve at the rear of the trailer was opened.  The air line was connected to the tractor’s compressor and the PTO was engaged.  The unloader instructed the driver he was ready to obtain the sample.  The unloader went to the acid shack opened the bleeder valve on the product line and was waiting to take the sample.   At the same time the unloader was waiting, the driver then opened the butterfly valve and ball valve on the air inlet line.  The hydro pack on the tractor was engaged and the driver was at the rear of the trailer by the product hose to wait for the product to began moving.  It was then when the product sprayed from the tractor’s compressor.  In response to the release the first butterfly valve was closed then the ball valve.  The air compressor was shut off, the external valve and finally the emergency shut off valve were closed.  With all valves closed product continued to flow from the air line for approximately one (1) minute. Estimated pressure on the trailer at the time of the release was 7 psi.     Plant personnel responded to the release by containing the release from air line into a five (5) gallon bucket.  The product went from a small stream intermediate drip over a 15 minute time span, three (3) gallons of product was collected in the bucket.  Plant personnel diked the released product with absorbent socks and neutralized with soda ash.      Faulty gasket located on the chicago  fitting of the tractor's air compressor.   The connection at the tractor's air compressor developed a leak at the gaskets between the chicago hook up. Further from an operational stand point this was caused because there was not enough pressure in the air line,  the gasket allowed air to pass from the trailer and out the air line which caused the release.
column169: Training and review of the incident will be conducted with all drivers and maintenance personnel,  part of this review will include inspection of worn gaskets and any issues that can arise from the loose connections.  It will be reinfoced that the conditions  of all gaskets is part of a driver's pre and post trip inspection, they must be changed frequently.  Drivers are given extra gaskets for this purpose.      A policy will be put in place effective immedatley that at all times  spring steel locking pins are to be used on all chicago fitting connections.   These pins in conjunction with gaskets that are in good condition will allow the chicago fitting to have better allignment and ensure a good seal.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A BNSF switchman in the railyard reported GATX 200696 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area. BNSF mechanical /hazardous material responders immediately inspected GATX 200696 finding product escaping from the safety valve (pressure relief device) which is indicative of an overfilled condition. Spillage on the side shell of GATX 200696 was evaporating. The responders reduced the internal pressure within GATX 200696 via the vacuum relief valve which stopped further product flow from the safety valve. GATX 200696 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting product reduction. A contractor assisted in off-loading excess product into a tank truck by 0100 hrs. PDT, 7/28/2010 without further incident.  Afterwards, the outage level within GATX 200696 measured at 8 1/4 inches which equates to 1176 gallons of outage per the GATX Outage Table.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and the mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings; including the gauging of proper product outages within the transportation package.

column168: A mist of KOH vapor came out of where gauge is inserted into tank, leaking approx 1/2 gal of material. When the leak was noticed immediately all lines were shut. The driver had just completed the blow down procedure and was in process of shutting valves when spill occured. Spill was cleaned up onsite immediately.
column169: Customer is looking into the reason the KOH leaked from the gauge, they are also looking into updating the venting and loading systems for that tank. We have investigated the incident and have incorporated communications into our training regarding the spill.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: An inbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard revealed fresh product on the side shell of TILX 260969 (AAR 211A100W1 tank car). TILX 260969 was immediately inspected by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder reported that the manway closure was the source of the product release. A detailed inspection of the manway closure revealed that the manway gasket was missing. The responder applied a new manway gasket and resecured the manway closure. BNSF seal numbered 002465 was applied to the manway closure. Spillage (tar like substance) on the safety appliances (side ladders) and side shell were cleaned. No ground impact from this product release was observed.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.
