column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: AT 1100 HOURS CDT ON 07/29/2010 I RECEIVED A CALL OF AN AMMONIA CAR VENTING AT THE INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) RAILROAD YARD IN RIVERDALE, ILLINOIS AND SUBSEQUENT STAND DOWN OF EMPLOYEES IN THE YARD.  WHILE RESPONDING TO SCENE I CONTACTED IHB HAZMAT CONTRACTOR "MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL" AND REQUESTED THEIR RESPONSE AS WELL.  UPON ARRIVAL OF MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL AND MYSELF WE NOTED RAILCAR GLNX 34542 EMITTING PRESSURE FROM THE "PROTECTIVE HOUSING".  SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AFTER REMOVING SEAL #TIC 146491 AND OPENING LID NOTED THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) WAS OPEN AND EMITTING PRESSURE.  WE WERE SUCCESSFUL IN RESEATING THE O-RING RETAINER WHICH WAS OPEN FOR REASONS UNKNOWN AND SECURING THE PRESSURE LEAK.  PRESSURE READING ON TANK CAR INDICATED 125 PSI AND THERMOWELL TEMPERATURE OF 80 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT RAILCAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY ISOLATED AND SPOTTED ON OLD RIP TRACK AFTER MOVING SAME AT WALKING SPEED.  RAILCAR WAS MONITORED DURING THE TIME FROM SPOTTING UNTIL DE-GASSING FOR SIGNS OF ANY LEAKS.  SHIPPER, "TANNER INDUSTRIES" WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.  IN CONSULTATIONS WITH THE SHIPPER WHOSE RESPONSE WAS EXCELLENT IT WAD DETERMINED TO DE-GAS THE RAILCAR INVOLVED TO RENDER SAFE.  ON 07/30/2010 SHIPPER ARRIVED ON SCENE WITH PERSONNEL AND TANK TRUCK FILLED WITH DEIONIZED WATER AND TOGETHER WITH IHB CONTRACTOR MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL SUBSEQUENTLY DEGASSED CAR BY TRANSFERRING VAPOR FROM RAILCAR INTO TANK TRUCK.  MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL REPLACED O-RING RETAINER CAP AND O-RINGS ON (PRD) AFTER REMOVAL OF ANY PRESSURE INSIDE CAR.  O-RING RETAINER THAT WAS REMOVED FROM THE (PRD) SHOWED EVIDENCE OF CORROSION ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE CAP.  I PLACED SEAL # IHPD 003923 AFTER SECURING PROTECTIVE HOUSING LID.  CAR IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD PENDING FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION (FRA) MOVEMENT APPROVAL.
column169: AFTER MOVEMENT APPROVAL IS OBTAINED, RAILCAR IS TO BE SHOPPED AND PRD REMOVED FOR ANALYSIS AND DETERMINATION OF FAILURE.

column168: Intermodal container HJCU 149454 that arrived on a BNSF train earlier was reported leaking an unknown liquid. HJCU 149454 was carefully moved to the intermodal facility's containment area. The shipper was notified and dispatched contract responders. The responders reported that several pallets of 5 gallon poly pails of product had shifted forward toward the nose of this container into voids left between lading. These pails shifted off their pallets with the lading stacked atop crushing some pails with others leaking from their lids at various rates. Non-impacted lading was transferred to another suitable container. Intact lading that shifted off their pallets were restacked and secured to pallets and placed inside the transfer container. Absorbent material was applied to the spillage inside HJCU 149454 and sweep into recovery drums which were left inside HJCU 149454 for the shipper's disposal. All the damaged/leaking pails were either bagged/taped closed or placed into overpack drums. These were also stored inside HJCU 149454 for shipper's disposal. All ground spillage observed was cleaned. Another contractor prepared HJCU 149454's contents for furtherance.
column169: Ensure shipper properly blocks and braces lading as outlined in the varoius loading guidelines and recommended practices published and pertinent to rail intermodal shipments.

column168: July 30, 2010: At approximately 0815 hours, CR Car Inspector reported product on sides of tank car TILX 261295, shipped as residue last contained Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, NOS, (Alcohol C-12 C-16 Poly (1-6) Ethoxylate), 9, UN 3082, PG III, Marine Pollutant, while located on #11 Support in Conrail's Pavonia Yard.  Car only wet on sides and not actively leaking.    Car moved to Notch Track for accessibility for equipment/personnel.  Further inspection by CR's A. Richter, REACT's (Conrail's environmental/emergency response contractor) M. Holon, and Shipper Stepan Company's D. Pratt (EHS+S Admin.) found product residue on top of manway (location of recycling vaccum relief device), in addition to the car's top center and down both sides.  Car had been unloaded by Stepan Co. in evening of 7/29/10 or early morning of 7/30/10; and switched from their facility 7/30/10, arriving at CR's Pavonia Yard for outbound CSXT train.    Manway cover opened (all bolts not totally tool tight) revealing a deteriorated manway cover gasket (garlock style).  Gasket replaced with Viton manway nozzle gasket after conferring with Stepan's D. Pratt (on scene).  All other valves/fittings inspected with no exceptions noted.  Car resecured, decontaminated and okayed for shipping to original destination.    With the car in residue service, it's unclear on how product was noted on top of the manway cover.  Car may have released product through both the manway cover and vaccum relief device when it was under load and moved to Stepan Company as a load.  Mr. Pratt advised heavy rains evening of unloading may have prevented Stepan personnel from noting product residue on car.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NO EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column58: Liquid Valve; Manway or Dome Cover
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Incorrectly Sized Component or Device
column168: KMKU 310 was reported to have a liquid release from the manway. Upon inspection, the tank car was found to have two releases. The first was an improperly sized manway gasket. The gasket was larger than the manway allowed. This caused the release of approximately two gallons of liquid. A new gasket was applied eliminating the release. The second release was at the liquid valve. The male threaded nipple at the liquid valve body released. The cause of this release was a less than tool tight liquid valve body. The valve was tightened eliminating the release.

column169: BLOCK THE LOAD TO RIDE BEFORE CLOSING TRAILER.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: On Saturday July 31st, 2010 at 06:00 the rail car orders went out to load the rail car UTLX 206076 with butyl acrylate.  As he was nearing the target gauge another Rackman in the area was asked to assist.  When the Rackman hit his target gauge he shut the loading arm liquid valve and asked the other Rackman in the area to close the loading arm valve at the bottom of the loader.  With pressure still on the rail car the Rackman closed the vapor valve on the rail car.  At this time the rail car liquid valve is still in the Open position; this meaning there is liquid under pressure still on the rail car loading connection into the hose. The Rackman then proceeded to release one of the cam-lock quick fit ears on the liquid connection.  At 09:12 on July 31st, 2010 after releasing this cam-lock on the liquid connection, the loading hose blew off the fitting on the rail car.   This incident did not involve failure of the railcar or loading equipment. The operator failed to close the railcar valve prior to disconnection of the liquid loading hose. At the time of the incident, the railcar was parked at an ITC railloading rack. The loading rack is designed with concrete containment routed to chemical sumps which provided 100% liquid spill containment. All spilled product was quickly drained into the chemical sumps to be treated at ITC's wastewater treatment facility. The loading rack was completely washed down to remove any chemical residues. The 190 lb reportable quantity is based on vapor release to the atmosphere.
column169: ITC's railcar loading procedure emphasizes the importance of closing all valves and releiving pressure prior to disconnect. Additional training will be implemented to re-enforce procedure. ITC will consider disciplinary action against the employee.

column168: An inbound BNSF intermodal train being unloaded at the BNSF intermodal facility was reported with a top container, JBHU 239784, leaking an unknown liquid substance onto the a container underneath it and the intermodal rail flatcar it was loaded upon. JBHU 239784 was deramped (unloaded from the railcar) and carefully moved to the facility's containment area.  J.B. Hunt contract responders cleaned the spillage from the intermodal rail flatcar and the container that was underneath JBHU 239784. Inspection inside JBHU 239784 revealed palletized 5 gallon poly pails (drums) had shifted forward into voids during transit and were partially crushed by the weight of lading stacked atop that had fallen onto them. The lading inside JBHU 239784 lacked the proper or sufficient blocking and bracing to prevent lading damage from load shift conditions either via highway or rail. Compromised 5 gallon drums of both hazardous material and non-hazardous material of floor care related products were placed into overpack drums. Shifted palletized non-compromised 5 gallon drums were restacked and secured onto pallets. Spillage inside and outside of JBHU 239784 was cleaned. Afterwards, palletized lading was returned into JBHU 239784 and properly secured for furtherance. Spent cleaning supplies were placed into recovery drums for shipper's removal.
column169: A BNSF Load and Ride Solution Manager notified J.B. Hunt's Cargo Claim office to apprise their origin loading customer of the proper load securement of shipments containing hazardous material packages.

column168: Operator measured storage tank to ensure 6810 gallons of material would fit in tank. He mistakenly calulated the 90% safe fill in the 12,000 gallon capacity tank to be 12,800 gallons when it is actually 10,800 gallons. The tank had 5435 gallons in it already and would not hold an additional 6810 gallons on the inbound tanker to be unloaded. The operator began to fill the storage tank from the tank truck unaware of his calulation error. He observed the storage tank beginning to run over and stopped pumping. 195 gallons spilled into the tank farm containment area. The spilled material was pumped into a tanker and disposed of properly. Entire amount was contained and cleaned up immedizately.
column169: Retrain employees on unloading procedure from bulk truck tanker to storage tank. Operators to fill out the receiving document using the complete 4 digit tank number to remind them of the tank size, for example 06 - - means 6000 gallon tank, 12 - - means 12000 gallon tank and 24 - - means 24000 gallon tank. Operator will also be required to have another employee double check their safe fill and amount to be transferred calculations to tank to verify there is capacity to hold material.

column168: PVS NORWOOD DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING NORTHBOUND ON I-275 TOWARD THE I-94 WESTBOUND EXIT AT POSTED SPEED IN EXCELLENT CONDITIONS WHEN HE OBSERVED A SMALL BOX-TRUCK STANDING IN THE ROADWAY AHEAD, DIAGONALLY STRADDLING THE MEDIAN AND ENCROACHING INTO A TRAFFIC LANE AFTER WEAVING THROUGH CONSTRUCTION BARRELLS.  AS THE PVS DRIVER APPROACHED THE STANDING VEHICLE, THE PVS DRIVER SLOWED AND SOUNDED HIS HORN.  THE DRIVER OF THE BOX-TRUCK THEN SUDDENLY ENTERED THE PVS DRIVER'S LANE OF TRAVEL CAUSING THE PVS DRIVER TO ATTEMPT TO  AVOID A COLLISION BY MANEUVERING RIGHTWARD OUT OF THE WAY OF THE ONCOMING VEHICLE.  THE PVS TRACTOR WAS UNABLE TO AVOID AN IMPACT BEING STRUCK BY THE SMALL BOX-TRUCK IN THE AREA OF THE LEFT FRONT (STEER) TIRE.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO REGAIN CONTROL BY VEERING LEFTWARD OFF OF THE RIGHT SHOULDER AND BACK ONTO THE  ROADWAY, BUT WAS UNABLE TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE FOLLOWING THE IMPACT, RESULTING IN THE TRACTOR/TRAILER COMBINATION ROLLING ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE AT 13 MPH. THE ROLLOVER IMPACT CAUSED ONE OF THE FOUR INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS (IBC'S) OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE 35% LIQUID WHICH WERE SECURED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER TO BREACH THE TRAILER ROOF AND LAND ON ITS TOP IN THE ROADWAY NORTH OF TRACTOR/TRAILER.  THE DAMAGE TO THE REMAINING FREIGHT WAS MINIMAL GIVEN THE  NATURE OF THE INCIDENT, BEING GREATLY REDUCED OR ELIMINATED ENTIRELY DUE TO THE APPLICATION OF PROPER CARGO SECUREMENT DEVICES BY THE PVS LOADERS IN PREPARATION FOR SHIPMENT. THE PVS DRIVER, STILL SECURED IN POSITION IN THE CAB BY HIS SEATBELT, CALLED 911 TO REPORT THE INCIDENT AND WAS INFORMED THEAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL HAD ALREADY BEEN DISPATCHED.  DRIVER THEN SHUT DOWN THE VEHICLE AND CALLED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT TO PLANT MANAGEMENT AND REQUEST THAT AN XATA INCIDENT REPORT BE GENERATED.  WITH SOME DIFFICULTY THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO DETACH THE SEALBELT AND WAS HELPED FROM THE VEHICLE BY MOTOR
column169: We are unable to suggest improvements to the packaging, which in our estimation, performed amazingly well under the circumstances.  However, one recommendation for future incidents would be for Incident command and emergency responders to more seriously consider non-destructive means of addressing incidents of this sort.  The recommendation was made strongly that holes not be cut into the IBC's as this would accelerate the release of material. Citing their concerns for safety of the response personnel, incident command chose an approach which, in fact, placed their responders at greater risk.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHINQUES FOR PAINT PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO ENSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM.  LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During offload at customer location, a leak occurred, which resulted in the release of approximately 1 gallon of free product.  The free product released to the loading dock, and concrete surface adjacent to dock.  Cactus Environmental Services of Dallas, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, product had dried to the affected area(s).  Product was contained to an impervious surface, and did not migrate to surface soils or waters of the state.  Cactus Environmental utilized absorbent material to attempt to recover, and used a pressure washer to remove residual product.  Two (2) 55-gallon drums were generated during the cleanup, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a leak during offload, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: 2010080572   T-chlor was transferred from original package into ROCK Totes originally used for flush water on truck T-74. Total quantity of T-chlor transferred was 550 gallons. This process was completed the afternoon of 7-20-2010. The Rock totes on T-74 are connected to a manifold on the truck with isolation valves. The totes are equipped with a bottom discharge valve as well.   After the product was transferred into the Rock Totes, the truck was parked in the southwest corner of the property to be utilized the next day. The truck operator did not close the valves on the totes or the valves on the manifold. Fluid began to leak from a two inch cam-lock coupling that connects the tote to the manifold via a two inch hose. On 7-21 -2010, initial discovery of the spill occurred.   Countermeasures incorporated absorbent sand as well as collecting the material with absorbent pads. Ecos Environmental and Disaster Restoration was contacted as well as State and Federal agencies for reporting purposes. Ecos initiated the testing process to determine the areas affected and made preparations for the cleanup process. PH tests confirmed that the material traveled from truck T-74 to the dirt parking area as well as to the drain in the parking area which flows to a retention pond.   Testing of the drain outlet completed by Ecos confirmed that the material had entered into the retention pond. Once this determination was made, the diagram for the storm water drainage was reviewed. The diagram for the retention pond includes a drywell equipped with a pump at the bottom to discharge storm water. Without knowledge of where the shutoff switch was located, the electrical panels were checked to try to locate the shutoff switch.   None of the electrical panels on the Champion property are equipped to shut the pump off. A call was then made to the Contractor involved in the relocation of the storm water drain to determine if the drywell pump was operational, as well as to find the shutoff for the pump. The Contractor was able to verbally describe the location of the shutoff switch at the west end of the retention pond.   The switch was turned off and the 2” pvc discharge line from the retention pond was visually monitored. The drywell pump did not activate after the switch was turned off.
column169: Time-line of Events (prior to, during, and after the incident)   • 6:30 a..m..- Spill was discovered at Champion Technologies Facility in Rifle Co.   • 6:35 a.m.- Employees on site deployed containment and absorbent material.   • 7:00 am..- Safety Rep. for Champion Technologies arrived on location and was notified that spill had occurred.   • 7:10 a.m.- Affected trucklequipment was moved to concrete containment to assess affected area.   • 7:15 am.- Employees removed affected totes and hoses from the truck for further investigation.   • 7:20 a.m.- Regional Safety Rep. and District Manager were notified that the RQ for the product was exceeded. Regional Safety Rep. began notification process to State and Federal authorities as well as Ecos Environmental Restoration for cleanup.   • 8:00 -9:30 a.m.- Ecos representative arrived on location for assessment of spill.   • 10:00 a..m.-Shutoff switch for drywell pump was found and shut off.   • 2:00 p.m.- Ecos cleanup operations began, storm water drains were cleaned. All fluids were placed into containers for disposal. All contaminated soil from the parking area as well as the retention pond was dug out and placed into roll off containers.

column168: A BNSF switch crew in the railyard reported PROX 33647 (DOT 112J340W tank car) emanating a product odor. Switching operations were suspended. PROX 33647 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. BNSF and contract responders inspected PROX 33647 and determined that the product vapor was releasing at the closed 280.4 psi pressure relief valve/device (PRD). The responders replaced the stem and seat o-rings in the PRD, ending the vapor release prior to 1100 hrs. CDT, 7/31/2010. The seat o-ring removed was visibly compressed, as well as, the flattened stem o-ring (Compression Set failure).

ON SATURDAY JULY 31, 2010 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 CST, A SEMI-TRACTOR TRAILER, PULLING A RAMP LOWBOY HAULING 2 PIECES OF LOGGING EQUIPMENT (SKIDDER AND CUTTER), WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON U.S. 59 IN THE RIGHT LANE.  AS THAT VEHICLE WAS APPROACHING A LOW OVERPASS (BNSF RAIL), A WHITE TOYOTA SEDAN THAT WAS TRAVELLING BEHIND THE LOWBOY CHANGED LANES FROM THE RIGHT LANE TO THE LEFT LANE TO PASS.  THE TPG TRANSPORT LLC CRUDE OIL TRUCK UNIT, IN TRAFFIC BEHIND THE TOYOTA, ALSO  CHANGED INTO THE LEFT LANE TO PASS THE LOWBOY.  AS THE LOWBOY STARTED UNDER THE BRIDGE, THE SKIDDER (WHICH WAS LOCATED FORWARD ON THE LOWBOY TRAILER) STRUCK THE OVERPASS AND CAME OFF THE TRAILER.  THE SKIDDER FELL ONTO THE TOYOTA CAUSING IT TO SKID SIDEWAYS.  THE TPG TRANSPORT UNIT ATTEMPTED TO STOP, BUT STRUCK THE TOYOTA AND THE SKIDDER; THE TPG TRANSPORT UNIT AND CAR CAME TO REST IN THE LEFT LANE JUST UNDER AND SOUTH OF THE CENTER BRIDGE ABUTMENT.  THE SKIDDER WAS KNOCKED INTO THE TRACTOR OF THE LOWBOY UNIT CAUSING IT TO GO PARTIALLY OFF THE ROADWAY JUST PAST THE BRIDGE SUPPORT.  ALL VEHICLES CAME TO REST UNDERNEATHE AND/OR PARTIALLY PAST THE BRIDGE ON THE SOUTH SIDE.  THE SKIDDER PUNCTURED HOLES IN THE TAYLOR TRAILER, WHICH WAS LOADED WITH UN1267 PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL, CAUSING AN ESTIMATED 13.5 BARREL RELEASE ONTO THE ROADWAY RUNNING INTO A STORM DRAIN INTO A DRY CREEK BED APPROXIMATELY 300 FEET SOUTHEAST OF THE ACCIDENT SITE.                                                                   THE DRIVER OF THE TOYOTA CAR WAS TRANSPORTED FROM THE SCENE WITH UNKNOWN INJURIES.  A PASSENGER IN THE TOYOTA SUFFERED FATAL INJURIES.  THE BLADE OF THE SKIDDER PUNCTURED THE DRIVER'S DOOR ON THE SEMI-TRACTOR/LOW CAUSING FATAL INJURIES TO THE DRIVER OF THAT TRUCK.  THE TAYLOR DRIVER WAS UNINJURED.  TPG TRANSPORT SAFETY DEPARTMENT CONTACTED EAGLE SWS FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE, CLEAN-UP AND REMEDIATION.  CLEAN-UP INVOLVED FLUSHING THE STORM DRAIN, THE REMOVAL AND OFF-SITE DISPOSAL OF CONTAMINATED SOILS AND WASTE WATER.  THE EXCAVATED AREA WAS SECURED WHILE AWAITING CONFIRMATORY LAB ANALYTICAL.  LAB ANALYTICAL REVEALED TPH AND LEVELS BELOW TCEQ CRITERIA.  THE EXCAVATED AREAS WERE BACKFILLED.

column168: Upon completion of a marine transfer from a third-party barge to the Hess Port Reading Refinery, approximately 2 gallons of residual fuel was released onto the Hess dock and dripped into the Arthur Kill below the dock.  The release occurred as a result of a communication error between the barge operator and the Hess dock operator.  Due to the communication error, the marine transfer hose was partially disconnected prior to the transfer line being fully drained. During the disconnection process, product flowed through the transfer line. Approximately 2 gallons of residual fuel splashed out of the containment pan and entered the Arthur Kill.                                                                                    Hess personnel used a boat to apply absorbent boom in the area in which the petroleum entered the water.  Hess brought in additional responders from Ken's Marine Service to assist with the cleanup.  Absorbent pads and sweep were used to remove any petroleum present at the base of the dock.
column169: Marine transfer procedures have been reviewed and modified to ensure proper communication prior to disconnection of the marine transfer hose.  The incident has been reviewed with facility personnel to ensure all individuals understand proper protocols.

column168: JADE TRANSPORTATION DRIVER ROBERTO SOQUI CAME ON DUTY AT 0545 MST IN BENSON, AZ. DID A PRETRIP EXAM OF TRACTOR #7, AND TRAILER #34T. HE STARTED DRIVING AT 6:00 A.M. EN ROUTE TO HAYDEN, AZ, ASARCO LLC ACID PLANT. ROBERTO ARRIVED FOR LOADING AT 8:15 A.M. AND COMPLETED THAT TALK AT 8:45 ON AZ HIGHWAY 77, A TWO LANE PAVED ROAD WITH PAVED 10' EMERGENCY LANES BOTH SIDES. AFTER SEVERAL MILES HE WAS BEHIND A UNLADENED OLDER FORD PICK UP WITH THREE INDIVIDUALS IN THE CAB. ROBERTO AND THE DISTANCE BETWEEN VEHICLES WAS 100 TO 150 YARDS. ROBERTO STATED HE HAD FOLLOWED THE PICKUP FOR 3 TO 5 MILES WHEN HE SAW A PERSON WALKING SOUTHBOUND IN THE PAVED NORTHBOUND EMERGENCY LANE EAST SIDE OF ROADWAY. THE PICKUP DRIVER, A 50 YEAR OLD RESIDENT OF MAMMOTH, AZ, SLOWED, PULLED TO THE RIGHT EMERGENCY LANE THAN COMMENCE TO DO A U TURN, 90 DEGREE ACROSS AZ 77 AT MP 120.2, WITH NO SIGNAL OF HIS INTENTIONS. MR. ROBERTO SOQUI APPLIED FULL BRAKING ACTION BUT MADE CONTACT WITH THE PICKUP BED AND LEFT REAR TIRE. THE PICKUP WAS PUSHED TO THE LEFT BUT DID NOT OVERTURN. THE PRIMARY IMPACK TO ONE TRACTOR #7 WAS ON LEFT FRONT BUMPER, FENDER AND TIRE. ROBERTO TRIED TO CONTROL HIS VEHICLE AND CARGO BUT THE TRACTOR VEERED LEFT, CLIMED AN EMBANKMENT AND ROLLED TO THE RIGHT. FOR A BRIEF MOMENT IT WAS INVERTED 180 DEGREE BUT CAME TO REST ON ITS RIGHT SIDE. THE OVERTURN PROTECTION DID NOT PREVENT THE BREAKING OF THE AIR INLET VALVE BUT ALL OTHER COMPONENTS GIVCARD VALVE, FILL DOME, ETC. SURVIVED IN DAMAGED.
column169: AZ HIGHWAY 77 IS "RURAL ARIZONA" WITH MANY SIDE ROADS INTO FARMS, RANCHES, AND PRIVAATE HOME SITE. LIKE THE FELLOW ROBERTO HIT, "I'M ONLY FIVE MILES FROM HOME I DON'T NEED TO BE AS CAREFUL AS I DO IN TUCSON OR PHOENIX." THIS GENTLEMAN WILL RECEIVE A CITATION FOR FAILURE TO YIELD PER OFFICER HAWKIN. ANYONE TRAVELING ANY HIGHWAY MUST EXERCISE DEFENSIVE DRIVING FOR EVERY INT YOU TRAVEL, ALL YOUR SENSES COME INTO PLAY, EYES ARE MOVING CONSTANTLY FOWARD, SIDE TO SIDE, BACK AND INSTURMENTS. EARS ARE TURNED TO OUTSIDE NOISE, WIND, ENGINE, TIRES, NOT THE RADIO. HAND REACT TO EYE COMMANDS BUT THEY ALSO TRANMIT TO THE BRAIN ANY ISSUE FELT IN THE WHERE OR OTHER CONTROLS. THE COMMERCIAL DRIVERS MUST ALWAYS BE IN COMMAND OF HIS VEHICLE AND BE AWARE OF NOT ONLY WHERE HE IS BUT WAHT THE OTHER VEHICLES ARE DOING. HE PLANS THE NEXT GEAR CHANCE AND ANY TURNS IN THE ROAD.

NOC realizing the exIting truck was not going to stop and yield, made a right turn maneuver to avoid encroaching Into on-coming traffic and the exiting vehicle, causIng NOC to overturn. The release was sudden. Initial response was by local EMA with a Hazmat Response team from Eagle Towning and Recovery dispatched withIn fifteen (15)minutes. Booms and oil dry were used to contain as much of the highway and parking lot api11 as possible. Booms were placed in the river to capture that which was exiting the storm sewer.
